data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new `Span<T>` / `ReadOnlySpan<T>` conversions mean `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (span-based) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`** (IEnumerable-based). Expression trees cannot represent span-based calls, so compilation may succeed but the expression **fails at runtime** when compiled/interpreted.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches ensure the expression tree binds to `Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)`, which is representable in expression trees and works with the interpreter.
